        <h2>JEWELLERY</h2>
        <h3>NATH</h3>
        <p>
            The Nath is a traditional nose ring, symbolizing marital bliss, and is an essential part of bridal jewelry in Uttarakhand. Garhwali Nath is large and intricately designed, often adorned with pearls and gold, while Kumaoni Nath is slightly simpler yet elegant. Its size and design often signify the family's cultural heritage and social status.
        </p>
        <img src="" alt="">
        <h3>GULUBAND</h3>
        <p>
            The Guluband is a choker-style necklace made from gold, silver, or beads, worn closely around the neck. It is a favorite among women in both Garhwal and Kumaon regions and is often embellished with intricate motifs. This ornament complements traditional attire and holds both aesthetic and cultural significance.
        </p>
        <img src="" alt="">
        <h3>HANSULI</h3>
        <p>
            Hansuli is a crescent-shaped neckpiece traditionally crafted from silver or gold, often worn during weddings and festivals. Its bold and sturdy design symbolizes prosperity and strength. This jewelry is particularly prominent among rural women of Uttarakhand, reflecting their connection to traditional craftsmanship.
        </p>
        <img src="" alt="">
        <h3>PAUNCHI</h3>
        <p>
            Paunchi refers to intricately designed gold or silver bracelets worn by women, especially brides, during weddings. These bracelets are sometimes studded with colorful stones or beads, adding a vibrant touch to the attire. Apart from beauty, they signify good luck and marital joy.
        </p>
        <img src="" alt="">
        <h3>BICHUWA</h3>
        <p>
            The Bichuwa is a pair of silver toe rings worn by married women as a symbol of their marital status. These rings are simple yet significant, often crafted with delicate designs. They are considered auspicious and form a key part of traditional Uttarakhand attire.
        </p>
